  "solution": {
    "answer": "No, $T^2$ and $K$ are not homeomorphic.",
    "steps": [
      "$H_2(T^2) \\cong \\mathbb{Z}$ and $H_2(K) = 0$: these groups differ.",
      "Since a homeomorphism would induce an isomorphism on $H_2$, no homeomorphism can exist.",
      "The underlying reason is orientability: $T^2$ is orientable (it has a well-defined global 2-cycle), while $K$ is non-orientable.",
      "Another invariant: $H_1(T^2) \\cong \\mathbb{Z}^2$ (torsion-free) whereas $H_1(K) \\cong \\mathbb{Z} \\oplus \\mathbb{Z}/2$ (has torsion)."
    ]
  }
}
